      "note": null
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_049",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "Es vigente hoy o en el pasado.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "It is valid today or in the past.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_049_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "It is effective today or earlier.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_049_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "It is active as of today or a prior date.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_049_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "It is in force today or in the past.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_049_sideB_3.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "English lacks a single 1:1 noun for \"vigencia.\" Instead, English uses adjectives or verb phrases to describe the state of the account.\n\nGrammatical Shift: Spanish uses a noun (la vigencia); English prefers the adjective ([effective] or [valid]).\n\n\"Iniciado su vigencia\" translates to:\n[Become effective]: Standard for contracts and official accounts.\n[Started]: Functional simplification for user interfaces.\n\nKey Industry Terms:\n[Effective Date]: The official term for when a document or account goes live.\n[Validity]: Refers to the \"legal life\" or period an item remains usable.\n\n~It is available today or in the past~ changes the meaning. [Available] means 'disponible', while 'vigente' means [valid] or [effective] in a legal or operational context."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_050",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "La cuenta debe haber iniciado su vigencia hoy o en el pasado.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "The account's effective date must be today or in the past.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_050_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "The account must have started today or earlier.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_050_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Account activation must date back to today or earlier.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_050_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "The account must be valid starting today or in the past.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_050_sideB_3.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "The account must have become effective today or in the past.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_050_sideB_4.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "The account must have started its validity today or earlier.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_050_sideB_5.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "The account must have taken effect today or prior.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_050_sideB_6.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "English lacks a single 1:1 noun for \"vigencia.\" Instead, English uses adjectives or verb phrases to describe the state of the account.\n\nGrammatical Shift: Spanish uses a noun (la vigencia); English prefers the adjective ([effective] or [valid]).\n\n\"Iniciado su vigencia\" translates to:\n[Become effective]: Standard for contracts and official accounts.\n[Started]: Functional simplification for user interfaces.\n\nKey Industry Terms:\n[Effective Date]: The official term for when a document or account goes live.\n[Validity]: Refers to the \"legal life\" or period an item remains usable.\n\n~The account must have initiated today or in the past.~ is unnatural because [initiated] is typically a transitive verb requiring an object, or used in the passive voice. For accounts, [started] or [become effective] are the correct collocations."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_051",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "La cuenta no tiene fecha de expiración.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "The account has no expiration date.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_051_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "The account doesn't have an expiry date.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_051_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "There is no expiration date on the account.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_051_sideB_2.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~The account has no expired date~ is incorrect. [Expired] is an adjective meaning it is already out of date. The noun phrase for the deadline is [expiration date].\n\n~The account has not expiration date~ is grammatically incorrect. You must use [has no] directly before the noun, or [doesn't have an] before the noun."
    },
    {
      "cardId": "dummy_052",
      "cardType": "flippable",
      "sideA": "O, si la tiene, esa fecha es hoy o está en el futuro.",
      "sideB": [
        {
          "text": "Or, if it does, that date is today or in the future.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_052_sideB_0.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Or, if it does have one, it's today or in the future.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_052_sideB_1.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Or, assuming it does, the date is today or later.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_052_sideB_2.mp3"
        },
        {
          "text": "Or, if it has one, that date is today or in the future.",
          "audioSrc": "public/data/audio/dummy/dummy_052_sideB_3.mp3"
        }
      ],
      "note": "~Or, if it has, that date is today or in the future~ is missing an object. The verb [has] requires an object like [one] to refer back to the date. It is more natural to use the auxiliary [does]: [if it does] or [if it has one]."
    }
  ]
}